      <div xml:id="NA338-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu oruvaḻit taṇantakālai āṟṟāta talaimakaḷ vaṉpoṟai etirmoḻintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE who was unable to bear it in the time [HE] has departed on a temporary absence said in the face of encouragement.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA338">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kaṭuṅkatir ñāyiṟu malaimaṟain taṉṟē</l>
<l>            vaṭumpukoṭi tumiya vāḻi pōḻntavar</l>
<l>            neṭuntē riṉṉoli yiravun tōṉṟā</l>
<l>            viṟappa vevva naliyu niṉṉilai</l>
<l>            niṟuttal vēṇṭu meṉṟi nilaippa</l>
<l>            yāṅkaṉam viṭumō maṟṟē mālkoḷa</l>
<l>            viyalirum parappi ṉiraiyeḻun taruntupu</l>
<l>            pulavunāṟu ciṟukuṭi maṉṟat tōṅkiya</l>
<l>            vāṭaraip peṇṇait tōṭumaṭa lēṟik</l>
<l>            koṭuvāyp pēṭai kuṭampaic cēriya</l>
<l>            vuyircelak kaṭaiip puṇartuṇaip</l>
<l>            payirta lāṉāp paitalaṅ kurukē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The sun with swift rays has vanished behind the mountain.</l>
<l>Even at night the sweet sound of his chariot does not appear,</l>
<l>crossing with [its] wheels so that they are severed the Aṭumpu creeper.</l>
<l>“In your state that is exceedingly afflicted by trouble</l>
<l>reflecting is necessary”,</l>
<l>you may say.</l>
<l>            How will it let go of [me] permanently,</l>
<l>            – the suffering crane(?)<note place="foot">Here the further description is not at all that of the usual <term xml:lang="ta">kuruku</term>, that is, a heron or egret or the like, but that of an <term xml:lang="ta">Aṉṟil</term>, the emblematic bird of couple life.</note>, with [its] calling unendingly</l>
<l>                for [its] mate to unite, impelling [my] life to go,</l>
<l>                while the she-bird with curved beak joins the nest,</l>
<l>                mounting the massed stems on the palmyra tree with swaying trunk,</l>
<l>                grown high on the village common of the small hamlet reeking of fish,</l>
<l>                risen for prey in the wide dark extension [and] eating,</l>
<l>                while darkness takes over?<note place="foot">What is conveyed by <term xml:lang="ta">māl</term> here? The infinitive clearly shows that it is not related to <term xml:lang="ta">parappu</term>. It might bring in the evening topos: night is falling now. It might also refer to HER state; metaphorically, the dark colour is a symbol for the dark moods.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
